#The figure suggests that the cuckoo is not found throughout Europe by chance, but is strongly associated with the climatic regions where its host species are present.
#It is noted that:
#most sightings of Cuculus canorus are concentrated in the ‘Cool Temperate Moist’ regions
#this same climatic region also has a significant population of Prunella modularis and Acrocephalus scirpaceus
#the cuckoo is much less common in drier and warmer regions.

#This is consistent with the ecology of brood parasitism.
#Furthermore, the two hosts appear to occupy partially distinct niches:
#Prunella modularis is very common in central-western Europe and in cooler regions,
#Acrocephalus scirpaceus seems to be more closely associated with wetter regions and lower altitudes.

#The cuckoo appears to overlap with both distributions, suggesting a degree of ecological flexibility and, likely, the ability to utilise multiple hosts.


